# 5 Results: Mnemonic Specificity and the Directional Boundary Effect

## 5.1 The Doppelgänger Effect (H5)

**Hypothesis (H5):** Highly similar lure items (Bin 1) are predicted to be significantly more difficult to distinguish from target items than less similar lures (Bin 5), resulting in a linear scale of discrimination failure.

**Model specification.**
A binomial logistic regression model (GLMM) was fitted with `Item Only` as the reference (baseline) group. Accordingly, the intercept represents the log-odds of a correct response for participants in the `Item Only` condition at the baseline level of `lure_bin`. All other coefficients are interpreted relative to this reference category. The `lure_bin` coefficient captures the change in log-odds of a correct response as lure similarity decreases (i.e., moving from more similar to less similar lures). The group coefficients (`Task Only`, `Both Item & Task`) reflect differences in overall performance relative to the `Item Only` group, while the interaction terms (`lure\_bin:group`) test whether the effect of lure similarity varies across task conditions.

```{r h5_logistic}
# Binomial logistic regression for Lure Discrimination
# We analyze the probability of identifying a lure as 'Similar' (Correct)
lure_data <- retrieval %>% filter(stimulus_type == "Lure")
mod_h5 <- glmer(response == "s" ~ lure_bin * group + (1|participant), 
                data = lure_data, family = binomial)
h5_summary <- tidy(mod_h5, effects = "fixed") %>%
  mutate(term = case_when(
    term == "(Intercept)" ~ "(Intercept) [Item Only]",
    term == "lure_bin" ~ "lure_bin [Item Only]",
    term == "grouptask_only" ~ "group (Task Only)",
    term == "groupBoth_item_task" ~ "group (Both Item & Task)",
    term == "lure_bin:grouptask_only" ~ "lure_bin:task_only",
    term == "lure_bin:groupBoth_item_task" ~ "lure_bin:Both",
    TRUE ~ term
  )) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~round(., 3))) %>%
  mutate(p_val = format.pval(p.value, eps = 0.001))

knitr::kable(h5_summary %>% select(term, estimate, std.error, statistic, p_val),
  caption = "GLMM results showing fixed effects of lure similarity (Lure Bin) on discrimination accuracy.",
  booktabs = TRUE)
```

**Result (Supported):** The analysis revealed a profound main effect of lure similarity on performance. As similarity decreased (from Bin 1 to Bin 5), the probability of correctly identifying lure items skyrocketed ($\beta = 0.196, p < 0.001$). This indicates that highly similar lures are massively vulnerable to being conflated with targets, proves that raw perceptual morphology inherently drives these classification errors.


```{r h5_interaction_plot, fig.cap="\\label{fig:lure_interaction} Interaction plot for Lure Discrimination. The linear trend is consistent across all cognitive load conditions."}
lure_bins %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = factor(lure_bin), y = p_similar, fill = group)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha=0.7, outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color=group), width=0.2, alpha=0.3) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = clr, labels = lbl) +
  scale_color_manual(values = clr, labels = lbl) +
  labs(x = "Lure Similarity Bin (1 = Most Similar)", y = "P('Similar'|Lure)") +
  theme_report
```


## 5.2 Trial-Level Boundary Effects (Boundary Wipe, H6)

To examine memory performance at the trial level, a generalized linear mixed model (GLMM) with a logistic link function was fitted. Participant was included as a random intercept to account for individual differences in baseline memory ability.

**Hypothesis (H6):** Items presented immediately after an event boundary (post-boundary) will have a lower probability of correct identification compared to pre-boundary items.

```{r h6_glmm}
# Summary of the GLMM for target accuracy
h6_summary <- tidy(glmm_mod, effects = "fixed", conf.int = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(term = case_when(
    term == "(Intercept)" ~ "Intercept (Item Only, Pre-boundary baseline)",
    term == "boundary_positionmid" ~ "Mid vs Pre boundary position",
    term == "boundary_positionpost" ~ "Post vs Pre boundary position",
    term == "grouptask_only" ~ "Task Only vs Item Only group",
    term == "groupBoth_item_task" ~ "Both (Item + Task) vs Item Only group",
    term == "boundary_positionmid:grouptask_only" ~ "Mid × Task Only interaction",
    term == "boundary_positionpost:grouptask_only" ~ "Post × Task Only interaction",
    term == "boundary_positionmid:groupBoth_item_task" ~ "Mid × Both condition interaction",
    term == "boundary_positionpost:groupBoth_item_task" ~ "Post × Both condition interaction",
    TRUE ~ term
  )) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~round(., 3))) %>%
  mutate(p_val = format.pval(p.value, eps = 0.001))

knitr::kable(h6_summary %>% select(term, estimate, std.error, statistic, p_val, conf.low, conf.high),
  caption = "GLMM results predicting the probability of correct responses at the trial level. The reference condition is the Item Only group at the Pre-boundary position.",
  booktabs = TRUE)
```

**Result (Not Supported):** The post-boundary condition shows a negative coefficient, indicating that participants were somewhat less likely to respond correctly after an event boundary compared to the pre-boundary baseline. However, this effect was not statistically significant ($p = 0.188$), and therefore the Boundary Wipe hypothesis (H6) is not supported.

In contrast, a significant main effect was observed for the Task Only group ($p = 0.012$), indicating that participants in this condition performed worse overall than those in the Item Only baseline condition.

No interaction effects between boundary position and task condition were statistically significant. This indicates that the influence of event boundaries on memory performance does not differ reliably across task conditions.

Overall, these results suggest that although there is a slight tendency for memory performance to decrease after event boundaries, this effect is weak and inconsistent at the level of individual trials once differences between participants are taken into account.

## 5.3 The Positional Boundary Effect (H7)

To examine how memory performance evolves relative to an event boundary, we analyzed recognition accuracy across three positions: *Pre*, *Mid*, and *Post*. This analysis explicitly includes the *pre-boundary* position to capture changes in memory performance before and after a contextual shift.

**Methodology:** To formally quantify this effect, we employed a Linear Mixed-Effects Model (LMM) followed by a Type III ANOVA. Recognition Accuracy (REC) was treated as the dependent variable, with *Boundary Position* (Pre, Mid, Post) as the fixed effect. Participant was included as a random intercept ($1 | participant$) to account for individual differences in baseline memory performance.

**Hypothesis (H7):** Recognition accuracy is expected to remain stable within an event (Pre and Mid positions) but show a sharp decline immediately following an event boundary (Post position), reflecting a boundary-induced disruption in memory performance.

```{r h7_anova}
# Mixed-effects model testing the main effect of boundary position on REC
# Satterthwaite's method for DF
boundary_mod_h7 <- lmer(REC ~ boundary_position + (1|participant), data = metrics)
h7_anova <- anova(boundary_mod_h7, type = 3)

h7_tbl <- as.data.frame(h7_anova) %>%
  rownames_to_column("Term") %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~round(., 3))) %>%
  mutate(p_val = format.pval(`Pr(>F)`, eps = 0.001))

knitr::kable(h7_tbl %>% select(Term, F_value = `F value`, NumDF, DenDF, p_val), 
             caption = "Type III ANOVA: Main Effect of Boundary Position on Recognition (H7).", 
             booktabs = TRUE)
```

**Result (Supported):** A highly significant main effect of boundary position was observed ($p < 0.001$), indicating that recognition accuracy varies across event positions. 

Importantly, the observed pattern does not reflect a gradual decline across positions. Instead, accuracy remains relatively stable between the pre-boundary and mid-event positions, followed by a pronounced drop at the post-boundary position. This indicates that memory disruption occurs specifically at the point of contextual transition rather than accumulating progressively over time.

```{r h7_visual, fig.cap="\\label{fig:rec_gradient} The Positional Gradient Phenomenon: Mean REC across event positions illustrating the systematic decline from pre-boundary to post-boundary positions."}
metrics %>%
  group_by(boundary_position) %>%
  summarise(mean_rec = mean(REC, na.rm=TRUE), se = sd(REC, na.rm=TRUE)/sqrt(n()), .groups = "drop") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = boundary_position, y = mean_rec, group = 1)) +
  geom_line(color = "grey", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 4, color = "#2c3e50") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean_rec - se, ymax = mean_rec + se), width = 0.1) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 1)) +
  labs(x = "Event Boundary Position", y = "Mean Recognition Accuracy (REC)") +
  theme_report
```


